{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778172638,"nonce":"SCCFqRxHKbGKIa3Z9/peTvHgBi0=","title":"Î”v metric: switch from peak speed to peak forward velocity","message":"**Issue.** `compute_velocity_inflation` (`src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py`) reports `delta_v_percent` based on `peak_velocity = max_t ||v_t||_2` (peak *speed*; norm of full 2D velocity). C\u0026S 2019 explicitly use **peak forward velocity** â€” projection of velocity onto the reach axis (initialâ†’target) â€” for their Î”v comparisons (cf. p. 8137 \"Statistical design\" and Fig. 1e).\n\n**Why it matters.** C\u0026S's robust-vs-LQG signature is *opposite-signed across the two velocity components*: robust controllers have **higher peak forward velocity** but **lower peak lateral velocity** (Fig. 1e arrows; Results p. 8139). Peak speed (the 2-norm) mixes these, and the forward gain partially cancels against the lateral suppression â€” masking the inflation signal that C\u0026S report.\n\nThis plausibly contributes to why the C\u0026S regime with faithful Eq. 15 Q,R gave Î”v â‰ˆ âˆ’0.04% (`test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` xfail diagnostic) rather than the +5â€“15%-ish C\u0026S behaviourally report. The flavor (a) âŠŠ (b) finding from that xfail test is independent and stands; what shifts is the magnitude of the C\u0026S-regime baseline.\n\n**Fix.**\n\n1. In `simulate_closed_loop`, project velocity onto the reach axis: `v_forward_t = vel_t @ unit(target - init)`, `v_lateral_t = ||vel_t - v_forward_t * unit||`.\n2. Add `peak_forward_velocity`, `peak_forward_velocity_idx`, `peak_lateral_velocity` to `ClosedLoopRollout` (keep `peak_velocity` for backward-compat, but it is no longer the headline scalar).\n3. In `compute_velocity_inflation`, base `delta_v_percent` on `peak_forward_velocity` (signed: positive direction = towards target). Also expose `delta_v_lateral_percent` for the orthogonal channel.\n4. Update `VelocityInflationResult` fields accordingly.\n5. Re-run `test_diagnose_synthesis_review_phase2_predictions` (rlrmp regime, k=10, was +5.44%/+12.82% under peak speed) and `test_synthesis_review_regime_comparison` (C\u0026S regime with rlrmp Q,R + faithful Eq. 15 Q,R, was âˆ’0.77%/âˆ’0.04%).\n6. The xfail test `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` may pass or change diagnosis with the corrected metric. Update its xfail reason / assertion thresholds in light of the new numbers; if it passes, remove xfail.\n\n**Out of scope.** `scripts/eval_diagnostics.py`'s `peak_velocity` kinematics field on trained-model rollouts is a different context (measured RNN behaviour) and not the immediate concern. May warrant a separate pass later.\n\nPart of methodology-fix phase â€” sibling of `74bfd86` (induced-gain analyser), `db35426` (Riccati teacher distillation), `c723082` (LinearDynamicsAdversary), `97c227a` (Riccati flavor-(b) extension), `2e5f643` (damping calibration). Phase umbrella `b557d4e` is closed (auto-closed on synthesis-review merge); live phase state in `b33e8da` comment thread.\n\nSource for the velocity-metric finding: synthesis_review Â§11; flagged in Î”v analyser design discussion.","files":null}]}